ose monitoring; target fasting glucose\u202f80‑130\u202fmg/dL.  \n- **Nutrition**: Low‑sodium, high‑fiber diet; limit saturated fats; consider referral to dietitian.  \n- **Vaccinations**: Administer annual influenza vaccine, pneumococcal vaccine (PCV20), COVID‑19 booster as indicated.\n\n**4. Monitoring & Follow‑Up**  \n- **COPD**: Spirometry every 12\u202fmonths; review inhaler technique at each visit.  \n- **Diabetes**: HbA1c every 3\u202fmonths until stable, then q6\u202fmonths; renal panel q3\u202fmonths.  \n- **Blood pressure**: Home BP log; office check q3\u202fmonths.  \n- **Cardiac**: Stress test in 12\u202fmonths or sooner if symptoms change.  \n- **Labs**: CBC, CMP, lipid panel q6\u202fmonths.\n\n**5. Action Items for the Care Team**  \n1. Update the electronic medication list with the new inhaled corticosteroid and adjusted metformin dose.  \n2. Schedule pulmonary rehab referral and send referral to the local program.  \n3. Arrange a smoking‑cessation counseling appointment within the next two weeks.  \n4. Order labs (HbA1c, eGFR, CBC, lipid panel) for the upcoming visit.  \n5. Document the updated treatment plan in the EMR and inform the patient of all changes, providing written instructions.\n\n**6. Patient Education Points**  \n- Proper inhaler technique (demonstrate and reassess).  \n- Recognize early signs of COPD exacerbation (increased dyspnea, sputum change) and when to use rescue medication or seek care.  \n- Importance of adherence to diabetes meds and lifestyle modifications.  \n- Encourage regular physical activity (≥150\u202fmin/week moderate intensity) as tolerated.\n\n**Conclusion**  \nThe revised plan addresses the patient’s multiple chronic conditions, optimizes pharmacotherapy based on current renal function and disease severity, and emphasizes multidisciplinary support (rehab, smoking cessation, nutrition). Follow‑up in 4\u202fweeks to assess tolerance of the new inhaled corticosteroid'}

