t weight savings and fuel efficiency.  \n   - *Aluminum* remains a workhorse for moderate‑weight structures where cost and manufacturability are priorities.  \n   - *Titanium* provides high strength at a weight penalty, justified in high‑stress, high‑temperature zones.\n\n2. **Fatigue Life**  \n   - Composite lay‑up design (fiber orientation, stacking sequence) can be optimized for superior fatigue performance.  \n   - Metals (especially aluminum) require careful stress‑concentration management and regular inspection.\n\n3. **Corrosion & Environmental Resistance**  \n   - *Titanium* and *CFRP* excel in corrosive environments (e.g., marine, humid).  \n   - *Aluminum* needs protective treatments; *magnesium* is rarely used due to corrosion susceptibility.\n\n4. **Manufacturing & Repairability**  \n   - Metals are easier to machine, form, and repair in the field.  \n   - Composites demand specialized lay‑up, curing, and repair processes, but enable complex aerodynamic shapes.\n\n5. **Cost & Lifecycle**  \n   - Initial material cost: CFRP > Titanium > High‑Strength Steel > Aluminum > Magnesium.  \n   - Lifecycle cost can favor composites due to lower fuel consumption and reduced maintenance (fewer corrosion‑related repairs).\n\n### Recommendations for Material Selection\n\n- **Primary Load‑Bearing Structures (wings, fuselage skins):** Use *CFRP* where weight savings are critical and budget permits.  \n- **Secondary Structures & Cost‑Sensitive Areas:** *Aluminum alloys* provide a balanced solution.  \n- **High‑Temperature, High‑Stress Zones (engine pylons, landing gear):** *Titanium alloys* are preferred despite higher cost.  \n- **Fasteners & Small High‑Stress Parts:** *High‑strength steel* or *titanium* depending on weight constraints.  \n\nBy'}

