**Step 1 – Analysis of Materials**

Aircraft structures employ a variety of materials, each offering a distinct balance of strength, weight, durability, cost, and manufacturability. The most common categories are:

| Material | Typical Use | Strength‑to‑Weight (Specific Strength) | Fatigue Resistance | Corrosion Resistance | Manufacturing / Cost |
|----------|-------------|----------------------------------------|--------------------|----------------------|----------------------|
| **Aluminum alloys (e.g., 2024‑T3, 7075‑T6)** | Fuselage skins, wing ribs, bulkheads | 300–500 kN·m/kg (high) | Good, but requires careful stress‑concentration design | Moderate – needs protective coating | Well‑established processes, relatively low cost |
| **Titanium alloys (e.g., Ti‑6Al‑4V)** | Engine pylons, landing‑gear components, high‑stress frames | 400–600 kN·m/kg (very high) | Excellent, especially in high‑temperature environments | Excellent – forms protective oxide layer | Expensive, difficult to machine; limited to high‑value parts |
| **Carbon‑fiber reinforced polymer (CFRP)** | Wing spars, fuselage sections, empennage | 600–900 kN·m/kg (very high) | Excellent fatigue life; damage tolerance depends on lay‑up | Excellent – inert to corrosion | High material cost, labor‑intensive lay‑up; requires autoclave |
| **Glass‑fiber reinforced polymer (GFRP)** | Secondary structures, fairings | 200–300 kN·m/kg (moderate) | Good fatigue, but lower than CFRP | Excellent | Lower cost than CFRP, easier to fabricate |
| **Metallic‑matrix composites (MMCs)** | High‑temperature engine components | 500–700 kN·m/kg (high) | Very good at elevated temperatures | Good | Emerging technology; higher cost, limited production |
| **Hybrid metal‑composite (e.g., aluminum‑CFRP sandwich)** | Floor panels, wing skins | 500–800 kN·m/kg (high) | Combines metal fatigue resistance with composite stiffness | Good | Balances cost and performance; requires bonding expertise |

**Key Performance Insights**

1. **Weight Savings vs. Cost** – CFRP provides the greatest weight reduction, directly improving fuel efficiency and payload, but its cost and production time are still higher than aluminum. Hybrid solutions often achieve a compromise.
2. **Fatigue & Damage Tolerance** – Titanium and CFRP excel in fatigue life, crucial for high‑cycle commercial jets. Aluminum requires more frequent inspections for crack initiation.
3. **Corrosion & Environmental Resistance** – Composites and titanium are inherently corrosion‑resistant, reducing maintenance compared with aluminum, which needs protective coatings and regular inspections.
