n fatigue life, crucial for high‑cycle components such as wing spars and engine pylons. Aluminum alloys, while lighter, have shorter fatigue lives and require careful design to avoid crack initiation.  \n3. **Corrosion Resistance** – Titanium and composite materials (CFRP, GFRP) are inherently corrosion‑resistant, reducing maintenance. Aluminum alloys need protective anodizing or cladding, while steel requires coatings.  \n4. **Thermal Performance** – Titanium retains strength at elevated temperatures (up to ~600\u202f°C), making it suitable for hot‑section components. CFRP’s resin matrix can degrade above ~200\u202f°C, limiting its use in high‑temperature zones.  \n5. **Cost & Manufacturability** – Aluminum alloys remain the most cost‑effective and are well‑established in large‑scale production. CFRP, while offering superior performance, incurs higher material and processing costs and requires specialized lay‑up and curing facilities.  \n\n### Recommendations for Project R4567\n- **Primary Load‑Bearing Structures** (wing spars, fuselage frames): Adopt a hybrid approach—CFRP for the longest spans where weight savings are paramount, supplemented by Titanium‑6Al‑4V in high‑stress junctions.\n- **Secondary Structures & Skin Panels**: Use Aluminum‑7075 where higher strength is needed; Aluminum‑2024 where cost and ease of fabrication dominate.\n- **Landing‑Gear & High‑Load Attachments**: Retain High‑Strength Steel or Titanium for their superior load capacity and fatigue endurance.\n- **Corrosion‑Sensitive Areas** (e.g., near fuel tanks, humid environments): Prefer Titanium or apply advanced protective coatings to aluminum/steel components.\n\nAll'}

